@NODE Defaults "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Default Settings@{ub}

    The default settings are used by every configuration which is started with
    the @{"USEDEFAULTS" link Usage} argument. At the first start of a configuration
    with that argument, Rainboot will prompt you to configure your default
    settings now.

    A GUI with the following options will pop up then:

    @{"Screenmode" link Screenmode}
    @{"GFX mode" link Graphicsmode}

    @{"Continue & Save" link ConSave} @{"Continue & Use" link ConUse} @{"Help" link Help} @{"Cancel" link Cancel}

    After saving your default settings, the GUI will no longer pop up when the
    USEDEFAULTS argument is used. It will use your saved settings then for
    every configuration which uses the USEDEFAULTS argument.

    If you want to change your default settings after you`ve saved them, start
    the GUI of Rainboot and press the button 'Default Settings'. Then you can
    change them.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Screenmode "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Screenmode@{ub}

    This cycle gadget allows you to set the screenmode options:

    a) Best possible: If you set this argument, Rainboot will try to get the
                      best possible screenmode for each configuration. 

    b) Use Screenmoderequester: If you set this argument, a screenmode requester
                                will appear every time when a configuration with
                                USEDEFAULTS argument has been started. You can
                                select the screenmode that the configuration shall
                                use then.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Graphicsmode "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}GFX mode@{ub}

    This cycle gadget allows you to set the graphics mode:

    a) AGA/ECS/OCS: This is the standard mode for users without a graphics board.
                    It runs on every Amiga system (AGA/ECS/OCS).

    b) RTG: This is the mode for graphics board owners. It works with the two
            most used RTG Systems: Picasso96 and CyberGraphX.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ConSave "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Continue & Save@{ub}

    This button saves the current settings and starts displaying the
    configuration. After saving your settings, the GUI won`t appear
    any longer when the USEDEFAULTS argument is used. It will use the
    saved settings then.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ConUse "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Continue & Use@{ub}

    This button uses the current settings but does not save them. After
    pressing this button, the configuration will be started with that
    settings. But if there`s another configuration with the USEDEFAULTS,
    the GUI will popup again and prompt you to configure the default
    settings. If you don`t want it to pop up you`ve to press the
    @{"Continue & Save" link ConSave} button.
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE Help "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Help@{ub}

    This button displays some little help for the default settings
    window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Cancel "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Cancel@{ub}

    This button cancels the GUI and quits Rainboot. The configuration
    will not be displayed then.

@ENDNODE
 
@NODE Warning "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Warning@{ub}

    This is only important for registered users:

    Do not copy any of the keyfiles by hand to any directory! Use the installation
    script provided! It won`t work correctly if you copy them by hand and your system
    may be harmed.

    If you`ve problems with the installation script @{b}contact@{ub} me first for help
    before you @{b}copy anything by hand@{ub}. Of course you can copy Rainboot to every
    place on your HD you want, but @{b}not@{ub} the keyfiles.

    Be careful!
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE GUI "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}The GUI (Graphical User Interface)@{ub}

    Starting with version 2.6 Rainboot comes with a GUI. It`ll pop up if no arguments
    were specified. There are several possibilities to do in the GUI:

    @{"Open             " LINK GUIOpen}
    @{"Display          " LINK GUIDisplay}
    @{"Options          " LINK GUIOptions}
    @{"Default Settings " LINK Defaults}
    @{"About            " LINK GUIAbout}
    @{"Quit             " LINK GUIQuit}

@ENDNODE
   
@NODE GUIOpen "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Open@{ub}

    If you press this button an ASL file requester will be opened, asking you for
    a configuration to load in memory.

@ENDNODE
    
@NODE GUIDisplay "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Display@{ub}

    If you press this button, the configuration which is currently in memory will 
    be displayed. Before you press this button you need to have a config loaded.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GUIOptions "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Options@{ub}

    If you press this button another window will open and allow you to set some
    different options:

    Screenmode: This can either be 'Best possible' or an other, user defined screenmode.
                It`s recommended that you use 'Best possible' because that selects
                the best screenmode for nearly every configuration.

    GFX mode: This can be ECS/OCS/AGA or RTG. Normally you should use ECS/OCS/AGA
              here, only if you have a graphic board you need to use RTG.

    If you select the 'Public screen' checkmark, Rainboot will open a public screen
    instead of a custom one.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GUIAbout "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}About@{ub}

    This will display some information about Rainboot.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GUIQuit "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Quit@{ub}

    Hmm, what might this button do?

@ENDNODE

@NODE Tools "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}Tools@{ub}

    I added several useful tools to the Rainboot archive which should help you
    to get Rainboot working as easy as possible. The following tools are currently
    available:

    GetModeID: A tiny program which opens a screenmode requester and lets you select
               a screenmode. After that it displays the modeid of that screenmode
               which you can use with Rainboot of course. If you want to open a hires
               640x256 screen and you don`t know the modeid, you`ll have to start
               GetModeID and select that screenmode. GetModeID will display now the
               screenmodeid for the selected screenmode, which is 167936 in this case.
               If you start Rainboot now and add the argument MODEID 167936, Rainboot
               will open a hires screen for you. 

    LoginMaker: This is a small program I wrote to let the users easily define their
                own login/password connection. If you`re starting this program the
                first time you can define the login and password you want. Attention:
                If you`ve already created a login/password connection and you would
                like to change it you`ll have to enter your old login & password to
                get access to change the login/password. You can only use one login and
                password connection. This connection will be used then by every 
                Rainboot config which supports login.

    RainCreator: This is a tool by Oliver Michel which allows you to create copper 
                 rainbows easily. The rainbows saved by RainCreator can be used with
                 Rainboot`s %COPPER keyword. Some examples of such files are in the
                 Configs drawer. They`re used by the Copper demo config. Have a look
                 at the @{"original documentation" link RainCreator} for RainCreator.

    RBLocaleCreator: This tiny program allows you to localize your Rainboot version.
                     You can enter the names of all days of the week and all month
                     of a year in your mother tongue. Rainboot will then display
                     if you use %TW the weekday in your language. But that is not
                     enough: You can also define the date format of your country!
                     The variables %d, %m and %y can be used here. Rainboot will
                     replace %d with the actual day, %m with the actual month and
                     %y with th actual year. Here in Germany I would enter the
                     following as date format: "%d. %m %y". This would print 
                     "4. Juli 1999", if we would have July 4th today :-) The locale
                     information will be saved as standard ascii to S:Rainboot3.locale.
                     Rainboot is of course Year 2000 compatible!!

    RBSSAdder: A really cool program by me :-) This program adds Rainboot3 automatically
               to your S:Startup-Sequence and it does even more: It changes your whole
               Startup-Sequence to work best with Rainboot. Of course a backup of your
               old Startup-Sequence will be made because I`m not sure if it`ll work on
               every system. RBSSAdder is integrated in the installation. It can detect
               if there`s already a Rainboot in your Startup-Sequence with the SEARCH
               argument. If Rainboot is already present RBSSAdder will change the current
               Rainboot line instead of creating a new one. You will most likely use
               RBSSAdder only during the installation.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE RainCreator "Rainboot3 Guide    Copyright © 1996-2000 Kimmo Pekkola & Andreas Falkenhahn"
@{b}RainCreator Documentation@{ub}

 RainCreator V1.0  (w) & (c) 1997 by Oliver Michel.
                   All rights reserved.

 This is freeware. If you use this RainCreator for commercial products
 you should send me a little fee ($5-$10),please.


 CONTROL:

  With the optional parameter   OCS   you can switch to the OCS/ECS mode.
  The palette has than only 4096 colors available.
  YOU MUST USE THE  OCS  PARAMETER IF YOU DONT HAVE THE AGA-CHIP OR IF YOU
  ARE IN OCS/ECS-MODE OR WANT USE THE OCS/ECS MODE.


  rainbow      - open the rainbow-editor

  info         - show information

  PAL          - select PAL-screen (usefull with `show`)


 rainbow-editor:

  Left MOUSE button   - set the left current line
  Right MOUSE button  - set the right current line

  The spread-function will use the range between this two lines.

  Select the LEFT or the RIGHT line with CURSOR LEFT/RIGHT or
  the button L/R.

  With CURSOR UP/DOWN you can move up/down the current line.


  load      - load the palette from a picture/palette (IFF of course)
  save      - save the palette (IFF)

  show      - remove the windows to see the rainbow in his full power.

  copy      - copy the RGB-value from the current line to the other

  spred     - spread the colors betwenn the left and the right line.

  swap      - swap the RGB-values.

That`s all folks. Let`s rain.

-<Oliver>-


